{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535668"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15501"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15501"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.43,0.29,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8192"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96729"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5389"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the general practice clinic for interpretation of a screening test result. You review a recent study evaluating a new screening test for colorectal cancer. The study included 2,000 patients. Of the 105 patients with cancer, 90 tested positive and 15 tested negative. Of the 1,895 patients without cancer, 285 tested positive and 1,610 tested negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the specificity of this screening test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24%","75%","85%","86%","99%"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of diagnostic test characteristics. The key components can be organised in a two-by-two table:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse:collapse;width:50%;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ECancer Present\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ECancer Absent\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETest Positive\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E90\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E285\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETest Negative\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E15\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1,610\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpecificity is calculated as TN/(TN+FP). From the table, TN=1,610 and FP=285, so specificity = 1,610/(1,610+285) = 1,610/1,895 = 0.85 = \u003Cstrong\u003E85%\u003C/strong\u003E. This means the test correctly identifies 85% of people who do not have cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the positive predictive value (PPV), calculated as TP/(TP+FP) = 90/(90+285) = 90/375 = 0.24 = 24%. This is the probability that someone with a positive test actually has cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E75%\u003C/strong\u003E is a distractor value that does not correspond to any meaningful calculation from this data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E86%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the sensitivity, calculated as TP/(TP+FN) = 90/(90+15) = 90/105 = 0.86 = 86%. This is the proportion of people with cancer who test positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E99%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the negative predictive value (NPV), calculated as TN/(TN+FN) = 1,610/(1,610+15) = 1,610/1,625 = 0.99 = 99%. This represents the probability that someone with a negative test is truly disease-free.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these test characteristics is crucial for interpreting diagnostic tests in clinical practice. Specificity is particularly important when a false positive result could lead to unnecessary invasive procedures or anxiety.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Specificity is calculated as true negatives divided by all patients without disease (true negatives + false positives).","Specificity represents the proportion of people without a condition who test negative.","A two-by-two table is a useful tool for calculating diagnostic test characteristics."],"references":["Trevethan R. Sensitivity, Specificity, and Predictive Values: Foundations, Pliabilities, and Pitfalls in Research and Practice. Front Public Health. 2017;5:307. Published 2017 Nov 20. doi:10.3389/fpubh.2017.00307","Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. (4th Edition). Oxford University Press Academic US; 2017. Chapter 42; pg. 442."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96729"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15501"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96729"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T19:40:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T19:40:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8192"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114726"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"